*{{cite web |url=https://cite.case.law/f3d/673/1089/#p1092 |title=Anderson v. Holder, 673 F.3d 1089 |page=1092 |date=2012-03-12 |work=Ninth Circuit |access-date=2021-09-06 |archive-date=2021-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211112052421/https://cite.case.law/f3d/673/1089/#p1092 |dead-url=no }}
*{{cite web |url=https://cite.case.law/f-supp/559/2/#p3 |title=In re Petition of Tubig, 559 F. Supp. 2 |page=3 |date=1981-10-07 |work=U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California |access-date=2021-09-06 |archive-date=2021-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211112052415/https://cite.case.law/f3d/712/543/#p3 |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref name="U.S. non-citizen national">See
*{{USCFR|8|1003.2}}(c)(3)(vi) (about filing a "motion to reopen" {{link-en|Removal proceedings}} with the {{link-en|Board of Immigration Appeals}} "based on specific allegations, supported by evidence, that the respondent is a United States citizen or national"); 
*{{USCFR|22|51.1}} ("''U.S. non-citizen national'' means a person on whom U.S. nationality, but not U.S. citizenship, has been conferred at birth under 8 U.S.C. 1408, or under [[判例法|判例法]] or {{link-en|Refugee Act}}, and who has not subsequently lost such non-citizen nationality.").</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Petersen |first1=William |last2=Novak |first2=Michael |last3=Gleason |first3=Philip |title=Concepts of Ethnicity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mkxdz_3d-oC&q=To%20be%20or%20to%20become%20an%20American&pg=PA62 |access-date=2013-02-01 |year=1982 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674157262 |page=62 |quote=...from Thomas Paine's plea in 1783...to Henry Clay's remark in 1815... "It is hard for us to believe ... how conscious these early Americans were of the job of developing American character out of the regional and generational polaritities and contradictions of a nation of immigrants and migrants." ... To be or to become an American, a person did not have to be of any particular national, linguistic, religious, or ethnic background. All he had to do was to commit himself to the political ideology centered on the abstract ideals of liberty, equality, and republicanism. Thus the universalist ideological character of American nationality meant that it was open to anyone who willed to become an American. |archive-date=2021-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210314234536/https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mkxdz_3d-oC&q=To+be+or+to+become+an+American&pg=PA62 |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Foreign nationals |url=https://www.fec.gov/updates/foreign-nationals/ |publisher=Federal Election Commission |date=2017-06-23 |access-date=2021-02-18 |archive-date=2020-08-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200821144200/https://www.fec.gov/updates/foreign-nationals/ |dead-url=no }}</ref>美國是許多[[美國種族及民族|民族]]的家園。因此，[[美國文化|美國的文化]]和{{link-en|美國國籍法|United States nationality law|法律}}並不把[[國籍|國籍]]等同於[[種族|種族]]或[[族群|民族]]，而是將其視作一種公民身份，也象徵着對國家的效忠。<ref>*{{cite web |url=https://cite.case.law/f3d/502/337/#p341 |title=Fernandez v. Keisler, 502 F.3d 337 |page=341 |date=2007-09-26 |work=Fourth Circuit |quote=The INA defines 'national of the United States' as '(A) a citizen of the United States, or (B) a person who, though not a citizen of the United States, owes permanent allegiance to the United States.' |access-date=2021-09-06 |archive-date=2021-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210830214914/https://cite.case.law/f3d/502/337/#p341 |dead-url=no }}
*{{cite web |url=https://cite.case.law/f-supp-2d/599/772/#footnote_1_3 |title=Robertson-Dewar v. Mukasey, 599 F. Supp. 2d 772 |page=779 n.3 |date=2009-02-25 |work=U.S. District Court for the Western District of Texas |quote=The [INA] defines naturalization as 'conferring of nationality of a state upon a person after birth, by any means whatsoever.' |access-date=2021-09-06 |archive-date=2021-08-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210830214920/https://cite.case.law/f-supp-2d/599/772/#footnote_1_3 |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://definitions.uslegal.com/p/permanent-allegiance/ |title=Permanent Allegiance Law and Legal Definition |publisher=definitions.uslegal.com |access-date=2021-09-06 |archive-date=2012-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025124037/https://definitions.uslegal.com/p/permanent-allegiance/ |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref name="Citizen">{{cite book|author1=Christine Barbour|author2=Gerald C Wright|title=Keeping the Republic: Power and Citizenship in American Politics, 6th Edition The Essentials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=40dPkS2aRZEC&pg=PA31|date=2013-01-15|publisher=CQ Press|isbn=978-1-4522-4003-9|pages=31–33|quote=Who Is An American? Native-born and naturalized citizens|access-date=2015-01-06|archive-date=2016-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424184818/https://books.google.com/books?id=40dPkS2aRZEC&pg=PA31|dead-url=no}}<br />{{cite book |last=Shklar |first=Judith N. |title=American Citizenship: The Quest for Inclusion |series=The Tanner Lectures on Human Values |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8n829DOw1PMC&pg=PA3 |access-date=2012-12-17 |year=1991 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674022164 |pages=3–4 |archive-date=2016-06-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603153611/https://books.google.com/books?id=8n829DOw1PMC&pg=PA3 |dead-url=no }}<br />{{cite journal |last1=Slotkin |first1=Richard |year=2001 |title=Unit Pride: Ethnic Platoons and the Myths of American Nationality |journal=American Literary History |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=469–498 |publisher=Oxford University Press |doi=10.1093/alh/13.3.469 |s2cid=143996198 |url=http://wesscholar.wesleyan.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1028&context=div2facpubs |access-date=2012-12-17 |quote=But it also expresses a myth of American nationality that remains vital in our political and cultural life: the idealized self-image of a multiethnic, multiracial democracy, hospitable to differences but united by a common sense of national belonging. |archive-date=2019-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108094920/http://wesscholar.wesleyan.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1028&context=div2facpubs |dead-url=no }}<br />{{cite book |last1=Eder |first1=Klaus |last2=Giesen |first2=Bernhard |title=European Citizenship: Between National Legacies and Postnational Projects |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lL-FiY6xhfUC&q=%22American%20nationality%22%20citizenship&pg=PA25 |access-date=2013-02-01 |year=2001 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199241200 |pages=25–26 |quote=In inter-state relations, the American nation state presents its members as a monistic political body-despite ethnic and national groups in the interior. |archive-date=2021-01-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120012825/https://books.google.com/books?id=lL-FiY6xhfUC&q=%22American%20nationality%22%20citizenship&pg=PA25 |dead-url=no }}<br />{{cite book |last1=Petersen |first1=William |last2=Novak |first2=Michael |last3=Gleason |first3=Philip |title=Concepts of Ethnicity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mkxdz_3d-oC&q=To%20be%20or%20to%20become%20an%20American&pg=PA62 |access-date=2013-02-01 |year=1982 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674157262 |page=62 |quote=To be or to become an American, a person did not have to be of any particular national, linguistic, religious, or ethnic background. All he had to do was to commit himself to the political ideology centered on the abstract ideals of liberty, equality, and republicanism. Thus the universalist ideological character of American nationality meant that it was open to anyone who willed to become an American. |archive-date=2021-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210314234536/https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mkxdz_3d-oC&q=To+be+or+to+become+an+American&pg=PA62 |dead-url=no }}<br />{{cite book|author1=Charles Hirschman|author2=Philip Kasinitz|author3=Josh Dewind|title=The Handbook of International Migration: The American Experience|url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofintern00char|date=1999-11-04|publisher=Russell Sage Foundation|isbn=978-1-61044-289-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/handbookofintern00char/page/300 300]}}<br />{{cite book|author=David Halle|title=America's Working Man: Work, Home, and Politics Among Blue Collar Property Owners|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1KCdTkq56zoC&pg=PA233|date=1987-07-15|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-31366-5|page=233|quote=The first, and central, way involves the view that Americans are all those persons born within the boundaries of the United States or admitted to citizenship by the government.|access-date=2021-09-06|archive-date=2016-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220010031/https://books.google.com/books?id=1KCdTkq56zoC&pg=PA233|dead-url=no}}</ref>

==概覽==
{{Main|美國人口}}
大部分美國人並非[[美國原住民|原住民]]，而是[[移民|移民]]和移民的後代。隨著美國領地的不斷擴張，[[夏威夷|夏威夷]]、[[波多黎各|波多黎各]]、[[關島|關島]]、[[美屬薩摩亞|美屬薩摩亞]]、[[美屬維京群島|美屬維京群島]]以及[[北馬利安納群島|北馬利安納群島]]的住民也陸續成為美國人。<ref>{{cite book|last=Lifshey|first=Adam|title=Subversions of the American Century: Filipino Literature in Spanish and the Transpacific Transformation of the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z17rCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-05293-6|page=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=Z17rCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA119&dq=%22the+status+of+filipinos+in+the+philippines+as+american+nationals%22 119]|quote=the status of Filipinos in the Philippines as American nationals existed from 1900 to 1946|access-date=2021-09-08|archive-date=2020-07-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200725101407/https://books.google.com/books?id=Z17rCgAAQBAJ|dead-url=no}}<br />{{cite book|author=Rick Baldoz|title=The Third Asiatic Invasion: Empire and Migration in Filipino America, 1898-1946|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J7QUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174|date=2011-02-28|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-9109-7|page=174|quote=Recalling earlier debates surrounding Filipinos' naturalization status in the United States, he pointed out that U.S. courts had definitively recognized that Filipinos were American "nationals" and not "aliens."|access-date=2021-09-08|archive-date=2020-07-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200725100856/https://books.google.com/books?id=J7QUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174|dead-url=no}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://fam.state.gov/FAM/08FAM/08FAM030205.html |title=8 FAM 302.5 Special Citizenship Provisions Regarding the Philippines |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020-05-15 |website=Foreign Affairs Manual |publisher=United States Department of State |access-date=2020-06-09 |archive-date=2018-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719010406/https://fam.state.gov/FAM/08FAM/08FAM030205.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>
<ref>U.S. Census Bureau. [https://www.census.gov/population/foreign/about/faq.html Foreign-Born Population Frequently asked Questions] {{Wayback|url=https://www.census.gov/population/foreign/about/faq.html |date=20151117174325 }} viewed January 19, 2015. The U.S. Census Bureau uses the terms native and native born to refer to anyone born in Puerto Rico, American Samoa, Guam, the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, or the U.S. Virgin Islands.</ref>
<ref name="American Somoans">*{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/u-s-nationals-born-american-samoa-sue-citizenship-n860721 |title=U.S. nationals born in American Samoa sue for citizenship |agency=Associated Press |work=NBC News |access-date=2018-10-01 |date=2018-03-28 |archive-date=2018-09-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928134312/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/u-s-nationals-born-american-samoa-sue-citizenship-n860721 |dead-url=no }}
*{{cite web |title=How a weird law gives one group American nationality but not citizenship |url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-10-11/how-weird-law-gives-one-group-american-nationality-not-citizenship |last=Mendoza |first=Moises |date=2014-10-11 |publisher=[[國際公眾電台|國際公眾電台]] (PRI) |access-date=2018-08-24 |archive-date=2018-08-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825074140/https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-10-11/how-weird-law-gives-one-group-american-nationality-not-citizenship |dead-url=no }}</ref>

美國的主流文化主要源自[[西歐|西歐]]和[[北歐|北歐]]，但也受到了非裔美國人的影響。<ref>Holloway, Joseph E. (2005). ''Africanisms in American Culture'', 2d ed. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, pp. 18–38. {{ISBN|0-253-34479-4}}. Johnson, Fern L. (1999). ''Speaking Culturally: Language Diversity in the United States''. Thousand Oaks, California, London, and New Delhi: Sage, p. 116. {{ISBN|0-8039-5912-5}}.</ref>隨著[[西進運動|西進運動]]的進行，路易斯安那的[[卡郡人|卡郡人]]和{{link-en|路易斯安那克里奧爾人|Louisiana Creole people|克里奧爾人}}、西南部的[[拉丁裔|拉丁裔]]以及墨西哥人的文化也對美國文化產生了影響。19世紀末至20世紀初，來自[[南歐|南歐]]、[[東歐|東歐]]、[[亞洲|亞洲]]、[[非洲|非洲]]和[[拉丁美洲|拉丁美洲]]的移民也影響了美國文化。在美國，各種文化一方面保持著自身的特徵，一方面又相互融合，因此美國常被稱為文化[[大熔爐|大熔爐]]或文化[[沙拉盤|沙拉盤]]。<ref name="DD">Adams, J.Q., and Pearlie Strother-Adams (2001). ''Dealing with Diversity''. Chicago: Kendall/Hunt. {{ISBN|0-7872-8145-X}}.</ref>

==種族和民族==
{{main|美國種族及民族}}
